      <bioghist id="aspace_7ccdcd964999e831e32c5c81e2d007d2">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Harry Kaigh Eustace was a big game hunter in Equatorial and East African jungles for twenty years, circa 1900. He was also a guide and scout, volunteering his services to British forces fighting in German East Africa. Eustace filmed the military operations as well as his hunting expeditions, obtaining some of the first authentic footage of Kilimanjaro, Taveta, Tsaro, Bura, Maketau Voi, and the Uganda Railway.</p>
         <p>After returning to England, Eustace became a renowned lecturer, narrating his films before British Royalty and geographical and zoological societies in France and England.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_9591b6de00942233fdfcbe027c18ed6e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers consist of a journal illustrated with pen-and-ink drawings which depict Harry Eustace's hunting and scouting activities in Africa. Photographs of Eustace and animals are also included as well as a flyer advertising his lecture "My African Hunt in War Time."</p>  
      </scopecontent>
